Refers to Ceuta, Melilla and reserved at the request of World Customs Organization (WCO). WIPO uses the code element "EA" to represent Eurasian Patent organization in its ST.3 standard without the consent of the ISO 3166/MA which in 1995 had set aside the code element "EV" for this
purpose. In fact, "EA" has for a long time been reserved for customs purposes to represent Ceuta and Melilla (see
Table 5) in the context of ISO 3166-1. So that the alpha-2 code element "EA" is now exceptionally reserved for WCO
(World Customs Organization), and also used like an indeterminately reserved code element by WIPO.

Refers to the former USSR and reserved at the request of the Foundation for Internet Development (FID). Remark part 3Removed from ISO 3166-1 in 1992 when former USSR was divided into: Armenia (AM, ARM, 051), Azerbaijan (AZ, AZE, 031), Estonia (EE, EST, 233), Georgia (GE, GEO, 268), Kazakstan (KZ, KAZ, 398), Kyrgyzstan (KG, KGZ, 417), Latvia (LV, LVA, 428), Lithuania (LT, LTU, 440), Republic of Moldova (MD, MDA, 498), Russian Federation (RU, RUS, 643), Tajikistan (TJ, TJK, 762), Turkmenistan (TM, TKM, 795), Uzbekistan (UZ, UZB, 860). NOTE: Belarus (BY, BLR, 112) and Ukraine (UA, UKR, 804) are not listed because they were separately coded in ISO 3166 already before the USSR was split.

Reserved from 2010-12 to 2060-12. The Netherlands Antilles was divided into Bonaire, Saint Eustatius and Saba (BQ, BES, 535), Curaçao (CW, CUW, 531) and Sint Maarten (Dutch part) (SX, SXM, 534).
Reserved from 1989-12 to 2039-12. Name changed from former Burma (BU, BUR, 104) to Myanmar (MM MMR, 104). See code element BUMM.

Reserved from 2006-09 to 2056-09. Code element CS was used for the former Czechoslovakia (CS, CSK, 200) then reused for Serbia and Montenegro. See also code element CSHH. Formerly part of Yougoslavia (YU, YUG, 891) before its split. See code element YUCS. Name changed from former Yugoslavia (YU, YUG, 891) to Serbia and Montenegro (CS, SCG, 891). See also code element YUCS. Serbia and Montenegro was then divided into Serbia (RS, SRB, 688) and Montenegro (ME, MNE, 499).

Reserved from 1993-07 to 2043-07. The Neutral Zone (NT, NTZ, 536) was divided and is now part of Iraq (IQ, IRQ, 368) and part of Saudi Arabia (SA, SAU, 682). The code entry (NT, NTZ, 536) was deleted from ISO 3166-1.
Reserved from 2002-05 to 2052-05. Name changed from East Timor (TP, TMP, 626) to Timor-Leste (TL, TLS, 626).

Reserved from 2003-07 to 2053-07. Name changed from Yugoslavia to Serbia and Montenegro (CS, SCG, 891) in 2003. Former Yugoslavia was divided into Bosnia and Herzegovina (BA), Croatia (HR),The former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia (MK), Serbia and Montenegro (CS), Slovenia (SI).
Reserved from 1997-07 to 2047-07. Name changed from Zaire to the Democratic Republic of the Congo (CD, COD, 180). See also code element ZRCD.

British Antarctic Territory is now part of the entry Antarctica (AQ, ATA, 010). Code element BQ was formerly used for British Antarctic Territory and has been reused and reassigned to Bonaire, Sint Eustatius and Saba (BQ, BES, 535).
